WEBVTT

00:06.256 --> 00:08.675
-(WIND GUSTING)
-(TRANQUIL MUSIC PLAYING)

00:25.358 --> 00:27.277
(ENGINE ROARS)

00:27.819 --> 00:29.863
(MUSIC INTENSIFIES)

00:32.615 --> 00:34.409
This is your first time
driving in the dunes?

00:34.576 --> 00:37.454
I've been on dunes before.
Nothing like this, ever.

00:40.582 --> 00:42.792
-ALBERT: We're still in low, right?
-WILL: I hope.

00:46.087 --> 00:49.424
-WILL: Whoo!
-ALBERT: All right, Will, not too fast.

00:50.091 --> 00:51.801
"Pay attention," is basically
what you're saying.

00:52.302 --> 00:56.347
All of that freewheeling I was doing,
better cut that stuff out.

00:56.890 --> 00:58.683
Think it's up there that it gets crazier.

01:04.773 --> 01:07.275
<i>Whoa. Good heavens.</i>

01:07.901 --> 01:12.113
-You only learn through experience.
-Don't want to learn too much today.

01:12.322 --> 01:13.698
(LAUGHS)

01:34.719 --> 01:37.597
WILL: All right, this...
this is a serious one.

01:44.020 --> 01:45.313
(MUSIC TURNS OMINOUS)

01:45.480 --> 01:47.398
WILL: <i>This is ridiculous.</i>

01:50.401 --> 01:52.612
ALBERT: Look out, ooh!

01:53.154 --> 01:54.989
-You ready?
-I'm ready when you are.

02:00.161 --> 02:01.287
ALBERT: Oh, my God.

02:02.664 --> 02:04.457
WILL: Whoa, it's a steep one.

02:05.166 --> 02:07.794
Whoo! (CHUCKLES)

02:09.045 --> 02:10.046
I got you, I got you.

02:18.680 --> 02:21.349
<i>This is a story about speed.</i>

02:22.058 --> 02:24.853
-ALBERT: Oh, my God, Will. Whoa!
-(WILL CHUCKLES)

02:25.562 --> 02:30.066
<i>Not how quick I'm shredding these dunes.</i>
<i>A different sort of speed.</i>

02:30.608 --> 02:35.655
<i>A hidden world where things go</i>
<i>so fast or so slow...</i>

02:37.282 --> 02:38.867
<i>we don't even know they're happening.</i>

02:40.285 --> 02:41.327
(MUSIC FADES)

02:41.494 --> 02:43.079
(SOFT WIND BLOWING)

02:49.419 --> 02:52.463
(ETHEREAL MUSIC PLAYING)

03:03.224 --> 03:07.854
You got your real, like,
Zen explorer thing happening right now.

03:19.365 --> 03:23.786
There's, like, nothing happening here.
(CHUCKLES)

03:24.412 --> 03:26.664
-There's stuff happening here.
-Mm-hmm.

03:27.207 --> 03:28.374
You gotta be patient.

03:30.627 --> 03:31.628
You'll see.

03:35.548 --> 03:36.674
<i>So here's the deal.</i>

03:37.425 --> 03:40.345
<i>I'm taking Will across the oldest desert</i>
<i>in the world.</i>

03:41.054 --> 03:44.933
And at each pit stop,
I'm gonna use state-of-the-art technology

03:45.016 --> 03:49.395
to try to reveal how much of the world
he's actually missing.

03:51.397 --> 03:56.694
<i>'Cause often, nature just whizzes by</i>
<i>too fast or creeps along too slowly</i>

03:57.111 --> 03:58.321
<i>for us to even notice.</i>

04:11.834 --> 04:14.170
WILL: <i>It all sounds pretty far-fetched.</i>

04:14.754 --> 04:19.592
<i>But apparently, this hidden world of speed</i>
<i>is everywhere.</i>

04:21.427 --> 04:23.888
<i>Even 80 feet underwater.</i>

04:26.015 --> 04:28.893
(DREAMY MUSIC PLAYING)

04:46.828 --> 04:48.621
(MUSIC FADES)

04:49.163 --> 04:50.873
(DIVING REGULATOR HISSING)

04:51.207 --> 04:52.792
DIVA: <i>Comm check, one, two, three.</i>

04:58.965 --> 05:02.635
<i>There are a lot of anemones. </i>(LAUGHS)

05:08.516 --> 05:13.438
<i>At first glance, it looks like</i>
<i>just hundreds of tiny anemones,</i>

05:13.896 --> 05:15.732
<i>anchored to the rocks.</i>

05:17.150 --> 05:18.609
<i>But film them patiently...</i>

05:20.111 --> 05:21.696
-(CAMERA BEEPS)
<i>-...then speed it up...</i>

05:22.196 --> 05:23.781
(LIVELY MUSIC PLAYING)

05:23.990 --> 05:26.617
<i>...and this miniature world comes to life.</i>

05:29.495 --> 05:32.081
<i>Because anemones are actually animals.</i>

05:34.083 --> 05:36.919
<i>And they do everything</i>
<i>you'd expect animals to do.</i>

05:38.880 --> 05:39.881
<i>They feed.</i>

05:42.175 --> 05:43.176
<i>They fight.</i>

05:44.969 --> 05:48.264
<i>They breed by splitting themselves in two.</i>

05:58.649 --> 06:00.777
<i>And even more surprising than that...</i>

06:02.487 --> 06:03.488
<i>they move...</i>

06:12.413 --> 06:14.540
<i>using a weird sort of gallop.</i>

06:26.677 --> 06:32.558
WILL:<i> Seems like down in </i>Fraggle Rock,
<i>anemones have to travel to survive.</i>

06:33.893 --> 06:37.188
<i>Just because those dudes look slower</i>
<i>than a parked car,</i>

06:37.772 --> 06:39.315
<i>doesn't mean they ain't moving.</i>

06:44.862 --> 06:48.408
<i>Same goes for creatures</i>
<i>that move fast as lightning.</i>

06:49.659 --> 06:51.786
<i>That's what Albert and I are after next.</i>

06:53.204 --> 06:54.414
But to capture them,

06:54.705 --> 06:57.291
you better have a cameraman
who's quick on the draw.

06:59.836 --> 07:02.964
The second it hits,
you have to be, like, on a hair trigger.

07:03.047 --> 07:04.549
-WILL: Hair trigger.
-And you have to get it

07:04.674 --> 07:06.759
exactly at the moment
that you see it, almost predict it.

07:06.843 --> 07:08.970
Almost predict...
I have to, like, lean into it?

07:09.095 --> 07:13.558
So it's like the Force,
I have to use the Force to push this

07:13.808 --> 07:15.810
and it's gonna record
the last two seconds.

07:15.893 --> 07:20.314
It's like recording the past.
The camera records the past.

07:20.648 --> 07:22.483
-It's rolling all the time.
-It's rolling all the time,

07:22.567 --> 07:24.694
and then when I hit,
it'll record the last two seconds?

07:24.777 --> 07:26.571
Yeah. Just because it's rolling so fast...

07:26.654 --> 07:27.905
All right. I'm just trying to understand,

07:27.989 --> 07:29.866
'cause I don't want to mess up
the thing you got.

07:30.450 --> 07:33.161
We're using an incredibly powerful
slow motion camera

07:33.244 --> 07:37.874
to try and capture one of the fastest
muscle movements in biology.

07:38.583 --> 07:42.378
But success is gonna be dependent
on Will's reflexes.

07:42.962 --> 07:44.046
-You ready?
-Yeah.

07:44.213 --> 07:46.048
You got it? Don't screw this up, Will.

07:46.591 --> 07:47.675
Ooh.

07:48.509 --> 07:50.678
(TENSE MUSIC PLAYING)

07:53.681 --> 07:54.682
(WHISPERING) Albert, be still.

07:54.932 --> 07:57.059
-(WHISPERING) I gotta adjust the camera.
-Why are you moving?

07:57.143 --> 07:59.770
-'Cause he's moving. He's moving.
-But just be still.

08:02.773 --> 08:04.275
He sees it. He sees it.

08:07.695 --> 08:08.905
There we go. Okay. Ready.

08:09.822 --> 08:11.574
Remember, get it exactly
at the right moment.

08:13.117 --> 08:15.244
(MUSIC BUILDS)

08:17.788 --> 08:19.081
Wow!

08:19.707 --> 08:22.210
-(CHUCKLES)
-Whoa!

08:24.003 --> 08:25.588
Damn, that's a crunchy bug.

08:26.797 --> 08:29.884
-How are your slow reactions?
-My reactions are great.

08:31.344 --> 08:33.054
-Let's see.
-My reactions are so good,

08:33.137 --> 08:34.847
I might be before the chameleon.

08:35.014 --> 08:36.849
I had to put it on the maximum delay.

08:38.643 --> 08:39.644
Oh, man.

08:42.063 --> 08:43.105
ALBERT: Wow.

08:43.481 --> 08:45.983
I have no idea whether I got it or not.

08:46.275 --> 08:49.278
But there is no way
I'm telling Albert that.

08:50.988 --> 08:52.031
Okay.

08:54.617 --> 08:55.785
WILL: No, I'm pretty sure I did.

08:56.744 --> 08:57.870
He's confident.

08:59.872 --> 09:00.915
So we slowed...

09:01.958 --> 09:04.210
everything down
by 40 times with this camera.

09:06.212 --> 09:08.589
<i>Let's see how quick</i>
<i>you needed to be to get food around here.</i>

09:11.801 --> 09:12.927
<i>Oh...</i>

09:14.303 --> 09:16.389
<i>Oh! </i>(CHUCKLES)

09:17.306 --> 09:18.599
<i>Oh, you got lucky!</i>

09:22.186 --> 09:23.521
<i>Right, let's zoom in.</i>

09:26.065 --> 09:29.151
WILL:<i> I'm just noticing</i>
<i>how that acceleration builds...</i>

09:31.028 --> 09:35.491
<i>and then, whoosh! Like, you just</i>
<i>don't see any of that in real time.</i>

09:36.242 --> 09:40.246
<i>ALBERT: That tongue goes from zero to 60</i>
<i>in just a few hundredths of a second.</i>

09:40.955 --> 09:43.499
<i>That's nearly a hundred times faster</i>
<i>than any supercar.</i>

09:43.958 --> 09:45.209
<i>Which is why we just see a blur.</i>

09:46.252 --> 09:51.173
That blur is happening at a speed
faster than our brains can actually see

09:51.257 --> 09:53.009
-and process the data.
-Yeah. Yeah.

09:54.927 --> 09:58.514
The bigger you are,
the faster life seems to be.

09:58.973 --> 10:01.142
The smaller, the slower.

10:03.269 --> 10:06.355
<i>That lizard's tongue</i>
<i>is one of the fastest movements</i>

10:06.439 --> 10:07.857
<i>in the entire animal kingdom.</i>

10:09.734 --> 10:11.777
<i>But there are some creatures</i>
<i>that have figured out a way</i>

10:11.861 --> 10:15.823
<i>to use speeds way beyond</i>
<i>what their bodies are capable of.</i>

10:17.033 --> 10:20.494
-(WIND HOWLING)
-(OMINOUS MUSIC PLAYING)

10:36.510 --> 10:39.972
DWAYNE:<i> Each fall, billions of herring</i>
<i>migrate into these fjords.</i>

10:41.724 --> 10:43.768
<i>And they're followed</i>
<i>by a fearsome predator.</i>

10:47.146 --> 10:49.106
(GASPING)

10:51.025 --> 10:53.027
Whoa! (CHUCKLES)

10:54.445 --> 10:55.571
It's amazing!

10:58.407 --> 11:02.411
<i>Problem is,</i>
<i>orca are 20-foot-long and slow.</i>

11:06.457 --> 11:10.753
<i>Herring are one foot long and fast.</i>

11:15.675 --> 11:16.884
(ORCA SCREECHES)

11:18.386 --> 11:21.138
DWAYNE:<i> So, the big whales</i>
<i>have come up with an ingenious solution.</i>

11:21.347 --> 11:22.556
(ORCA SCREECHES)

11:24.684 --> 11:26.936
DWAYNE:<i> Something far too fast to see.</i>

11:27.061 --> 11:28.437
(ORCA SCREECHES)

11:28.521 --> 11:30.731
DWAYNE: <i>But I just might be able to hear.</i>

11:40.533 --> 11:44.286
-(UNDERWATER RUMBLING)
-DWAYNE: That was it!

11:45.162 --> 11:46.622
-(ORCA SCREECHING)
-Whoa!

11:59.093 --> 12:00.886
<i>That's the sound of an orca</i>

12:01.220 --> 12:04.557
<i>creating a shock wave</i>
<i>by slapping its tail.</i>

12:11.272 --> 12:13.524
(SHOCK WAVE BOOMING)

12:13.691 --> 12:15.776
DWAYNE: <i>That pulse</i>
<i>can travel through the water</i>

12:15.860 --> 12:17.737
<i>at more than a thousand miles an hour.</i>

12:20.448 --> 12:21.866
<i>And it stuns the herring,</i>

12:22.199 --> 12:24.118
<i>-knocking them out cold...</i>
-(ORCA SCREECHES)

12:27.663 --> 12:29.999
DWAYNE:<i> ...so the orca</i>
<i>can just scoop them up.</i>

12:30.332 --> 12:32.585
(ORCAS SCREECHING)

12:33.169 --> 12:34.170
DWAYNE: <i>Genius.</i>

12:37.923 --> 12:40.342
WILL: <i>Speed isn't just about</i>
<i>the animals though.</i>

12:42.261 --> 12:45.765
<i>The water itself is working</i>
<i>in ways we can't see.</i>

12:48.559 --> 12:52.730
<i>And even in a desert,</i>
<i>Albert's found a way to show me how.</i>

12:55.065 --> 12:57.151
Now, that is something
I was not expecting.

12:58.819 --> 12:59.945
ALBERT: Look at that!

13:06.118 --> 13:09.371
That's one of the most
crocodile-infested rivers in Africa.

13:09.872 --> 13:13.834
They say there's three people a week
who get bit by a crocodile on this river.

13:14.376 --> 13:17.296
Let's not add to that. (LAUGHS)

13:21.425 --> 13:22.468
ALBERT: <i>And the thing is,</i>

13:22.968 --> 13:25.805
to see what I want to see,
I have to get the perfect camera angle.

13:27.556 --> 13:30.392
<i>Which means that Will and I have to get</i>
<i>to the other side of that river.</i>

13:31.185 --> 13:33.145
WILL: So is there a bridge or something?

13:33.646 --> 13:35.815
-ALBERT: I got a little drone.
-All right.

13:36.357 --> 13:38.776
ALBERT: Maybe I can fly
a line out to the other side,

13:38.859 --> 13:41.862
around one of those big trees,
and we can get across onto the other side

13:41.987 --> 13:44.073
and see if we can see more of the falls.
Do you wanna to do that?

13:44.156 --> 13:48.035
Well, I hope you can do that,
'cause I have a hard time

13:48.118 --> 13:51.497
getting my remote to put the right stuff
on the TV I want.

13:51.580 --> 13:54.667
So, if you can fly a drone with a line,
I'm with you.

13:55.543 --> 13:57.878
-(CHUCKLES)
-(LAUGHS)

13:58.796 --> 14:00.130
(GRUNTS) That should probably do it.

14:00.798 --> 14:01.966
-Yeah. Are you ready?
-WILL: Yeah.

14:02.299 --> 14:03.759
-Watch out for the rotors.
-WILL: Yeah.

14:04.760 --> 14:05.761
ALBERT: Okay, I'm gonna go.

14:13.185 --> 14:17.648
The idea is to fly the light line
around the tree on the other side.

14:18.816 --> 14:21.777
And then we'll use that line
to pull a heavy climbing rope across.

14:23.654 --> 14:27.283
That's some MacGyver vibes you got going.
Coming down.

14:27.825 --> 14:28.993
ALBERT: Landing.

14:29.827 --> 14:31.328
-Good job.
-WILL: Love that.

14:31.412 --> 14:33.038
ALBERT: Now we'll tie
the line around this,

14:33.205 --> 14:35.291
pull it around. I'll go across.

14:36.542 --> 14:37.626
Hopefully, I won't fall.

14:38.919 --> 14:40.004
And then pull you across.

14:41.130 --> 14:43.799
'Cause there's really, like,
no room for error here.

14:44.466 --> 14:45.551
You got me nervous.

14:46.677 --> 14:47.678
All right.

14:50.264 --> 14:51.265
(SIGHS)

14:52.892 --> 14:55.811
-Looks good? Anything dangling?
-Just you.

14:55.895 --> 14:57.688
-(ALBERT LAUGHS)
-(CHUCKLES)

14:59.773 --> 15:01.358
-ALBERT: Ready?
-See you on the other side.

15:01.483 --> 15:02.526
ALBERT: Yeah.

15:02.651 --> 15:04.612
(INTENSE MUSIC PLAYING)

15:08.324 --> 15:09.658
WILL:<i> I am not gonna lie.</i>

15:10.534 --> 15:15.539
I sometimes forget about Albert's leg,
he just moves so well.

15:19.001 --> 15:22.087
<i>'Cause, of course,</i>
<i>his prosthetic leg is as high-tech</i>

15:22.171 --> 15:23.547
<i>as everything else about him.</i>

15:25.299 --> 15:27.593
-There you go.
-ALBERT: Made it.

15:32.139 --> 15:34.391
-You got me?
-ALBERT: I got you.

15:48.072 --> 15:50.532
Little further. Keep going.

15:52.910 --> 15:55.913
(DRAMATIC MUSIC PLAYING)

16:06.924 --> 16:07.925
ALBERT: Look down!

16:10.344 --> 16:11.428
Yeah!

16:36.286 --> 16:37.830
(MUSIC FADES)

16:37.955 --> 16:38.956
Hey.

16:40.833 --> 16:41.875
(CHUCKLES)

16:42.918 --> 16:44.628
(SIGHS) Oh, that's a man-tester.

16:44.712 --> 16:46.213
-(CHUCKLES)
-(LAUGHS)

16:47.339 --> 16:49.258
-Jeez.
-ALBERT: You glad we did it?

16:49.883 --> 16:52.177
WILL: Oh, yeah. You're always happy
you did it afterwards.

16:53.095 --> 16:56.932
In a movie,
my stuntman would've did that. (LAUGHS)

16:57.850 --> 16:59.560
-ALBERT: No stuntman here.
-(WILL LAUGHS)

16:59.643 --> 17:00.853
ALBERT: No stuntman here.

17:05.107 --> 17:08.485
WILL: <i>Truth be told,</i>
<i>Albert doesn't need a stuntman.</i>

17:09.194 --> 17:11.905
<i>My man here just takes it all</i>
<i>in his stride.</i>

17:13.115 --> 17:14.533
<i>And more power to him.</i>

17:15.242 --> 17:18.954
<i>'Cause you'd have thought losing a leg</i>
<i>would've stopped him in his tracks.</i>

17:21.290 --> 17:24.168
It's incredible when you can look back
at a single moment

17:25.002 --> 17:27.254
and realize just
how important it was. (CHUCKLES)

17:28.297 --> 17:31.508
I was riding along
with a friend in a vehicle...

17:32.885 --> 17:36.472
<i>and then in an instant,</i>
<i>everything begins to slow down,</i>

17:37.473 --> 17:39.767
<i>all reality seemed to shift.</i>

17:40.476 --> 17:41.477
<i>Boom!</i>

17:42.936 --> 17:44.688
I lost my leg in that car accident.

17:47.357 --> 17:53.030
But technology has helped me
be able to define my own limitations.

17:54.281 --> 17:55.741
You know, strangely,
I don't actually feel like

17:55.824 --> 17:58.827
I've lost anything,
I actually feel like I've gained.

18:00.871 --> 18:03.791
<i>It transformed who I am.</i>

18:05.000 --> 18:08.295
It gave me insights into a reality
that I wouldn't have seen otherwise.

18:15.969 --> 18:16.970
-(WILL GROANING)
-ALBERT: Okay.

18:17.054 --> 18:19.598
-Let's build the camera rig right here.
-WILL: Whoo!

18:26.313 --> 18:27.981
You got a lot of high-tech gear.

18:29.024 --> 18:31.693
ALBERT: Well, we're trying to capture
some pretty extreme speeds.

18:33.195 --> 18:36.824
Let's not forget what we're up to here.
We're trying to see the invisible.

18:48.043 --> 18:50.420
-ALBERT: How's the image?
-WILL: It's gorgeous.

18:50.712 --> 18:52.256
ALBERT: Great, ready when you are.

18:53.090 --> 18:54.091
Action.

18:58.053 --> 19:00.222
ALBERT:<i> Close up and slowed down...</i>

19:01.473 --> 19:04.226
<i>you see the waterfall</i>
<i>for what it really is.</i>

19:04.726 --> 19:06.061
(DROPLETS CRASHING)

19:06.270 --> 19:07.354
ALBERT: <i>Millions...</i>

19:08.438 --> 19:10.149
<i>of tiny explosions.</i>

19:21.076 --> 19:25.455
<i>Watch even closer, and you see that</i>
<i>each droplet is constantly changing shape.</i>

19:27.916 --> 19:31.879
<i>The biggest ones turn into parachutes</i>
<i>and then blow apart.</i>

19:36.008 --> 19:38.302
Okay, now let's change speed

19:38.385 --> 19:41.180
and look at the whole waterfall,
but in time-lapse.

19:46.852 --> 19:51.023
WILL:<i> Wow, that's beautiful.</i>
<i>It's totally different.</i>

19:53.108 --> 19:54.651
ALBERT: Just look at those ravines!

19:55.402 --> 19:58.864
WILL:<i> All of those tiny explosions</i>
<i>have completely smoothed out.</i>

20:00.115 --> 20:01.950
When you look at it like that...

20:03.452 --> 20:08.707
it almost is obvious
that the water is sawing the rocks away.

20:08.957 --> 20:10.334
Right? When you look at it like that.

20:10.417 --> 20:13.545
It's like, "Oh, yeah. Obviously,
that's cutting the rock."

20:16.256 --> 20:20.427
<i>At this speed, we are literally seeing</i>
<i>how the face of the Earth changes.</i>

20:22.429 --> 20:25.849
It's a completely
different experience of it.

20:29.811 --> 20:32.731
<i>There's one more stop on this crazy trip.</i>

20:34.608 --> 20:37.694
<i>To see something</i>
<i>even Albert's cameras can't reveal.</i>

20:40.405 --> 20:42.783
<i>But apparently, we can only get there</i>

20:43.283 --> 20:46.411
by leaping into a giant hole
in the ground.

20:47.663 --> 20:50.082
<i>Because of course we do.</i>

20:50.749 --> 20:51.792
Coming down.

20:53.919 --> 20:56.380
(DRAMATIC MUSIC PLAYING)

21:31.373 --> 21:32.499
(MUSIC FADES)

21:32.624 --> 21:33.709
WILL: Wow.

21:35.669 --> 21:36.962
This is crazy.

21:41.216 --> 21:42.592
It's huge.

21:44.136 --> 21:46.638
So, it's like there's a cave
that goes around back there,

21:46.722 --> 21:49.599
and a cave that goes back there.

21:54.271 --> 21:57.941
In all of the hours
it took us to get here,

21:58.650 --> 22:01.945
not for one moment did it look like
there was anywhere

22:02.029 --> 22:03.405
that you could go scuba diving.

22:03.613 --> 22:05.073
(BOTH LAUGH)

22:05.240 --> 22:06.450
ALBERT: Just goes to show you.

22:08.785 --> 22:13.832
Can you tell anything about what might be
under the water based on what's out here?

22:15.292 --> 22:17.836
Well, I think there's only one way
to find out.

22:18.337 --> 22:19.755
And that's by going in, right?

22:24.551 --> 22:27.596
I bet we can get down around here
and maybe enter in over here?

22:29.348 --> 22:33.643
WILL: <i>I'm not entirely sure</i>
<i>how Albert gets me to agree to this stuff.</i>

22:34.019 --> 22:37.314
He's like, "Trust me, Will.
Trust me. This isn't dangerous."

22:38.398 --> 22:39.399
Mm-hmm.

22:40.108 --> 22:42.444
-ALBERT: You feel good?
-Yeah. Just pop down and pop up.

22:42.569 --> 22:43.904
ALBERT: Okay. Ready?

22:55.082 --> 22:57.542
(EERIE MUSIC PLAYING)

23:14.768 --> 23:17.771
ALBERT: <i>This is one of the biggest</i>
<i>underground lakes in the world.</i>

23:20.065 --> 23:22.067
<i>At least 600 feet deep.</i>

23:25.237 --> 23:27.406
<i>And this is why we came here.</i>

23:28.281 --> 23:32.953
<i>Stalactites. One of the</i>
<i>slowest-growing things on the planet.</i>

23:36.915 --> 23:39.459
<i>By measuring them, we can go back in time.</i>

23:42.879 --> 23:45.590
<i>Each inch takes a thousand years to grow.</i>

23:47.426 --> 23:49.553
<i>Meaning this one has been here</i>

23:49.636 --> 23:52.472
<i>for more than 150,000 years.</i>

23:55.100 --> 23:57.727
<i>But these stalactites,</i>
<i>they're not just old.</i>

23:58.854 --> 24:00.105
<i>They're time capsules.</i>

24:03.150 --> 24:05.986
<i>As stalactites form, drip by drip...</i>

24:08.613 --> 24:11.825
<i>tiny fragments of air and soil</i>
<i>get trapped inside.</i>

24:14.077 --> 24:15.954
(ICE CRACKING)

24:18.498 --> 24:20.500
ALBERT:<i> Snapshots</i>
<i>of our planet that stretch</i>

24:21.168 --> 24:22.919
<i>way back before us humans were here.</i>

24:24.171 --> 24:25.213
<i>Every drought...</i>

24:28.133 --> 24:29.342
<i>every flood...</i>

24:31.553 --> 24:32.804
<i>every ice age...</i>

24:36.308 --> 24:42.147
<i>every forest fire is timestamped</i>
<i>and recorded forever.</i>

24:44.441 --> 24:46.985
<i>The speed that the Earth has changed...</i>

24:49.154 --> 24:52.199
<i>captured on</i>
<i>the ultimate time-lapse camera.</i>

24:58.747 --> 25:00.582
-ALBERT: Whoo-hoo!
-Yeah.

25:01.541 --> 25:02.626
ALBERT: That was incredible.

25:03.001 --> 25:05.253
That's ridiculous, I didn't think
it was gonna be that deep.

25:05.337 --> 25:07.464
(BOTH LAUGH)

25:07.714 --> 25:10.467
-It just kept going.
-(ALBERT SIGHS)

25:11.259 --> 25:12.511
Okay, it was scary.

25:12.761 --> 25:14.721
-I'm going to be honest. (LAUGHS)
-(LAUGHS)

25:14.804 --> 25:16.139
-I'm gonna keep it real.
-Oh, man.

25:16.264 --> 25:18.225
I'm gonna keep it real.
It was terrifying.

25:18.308 --> 25:20.769
(BOTH LAUGH)

25:24.689 --> 25:27.734
WILL: That's about as epic
an undertaking as I've ever...

25:27.859 --> 25:29.528
-(ALBERT CHUCKLING)
-WILL: (CHUCKLING) ...been a part of.

25:30.403 --> 25:31.905
What's crazy is the terrain.

25:32.030 --> 25:35.534
You just never expect
that's under the ground.

25:35.825 --> 25:37.536
-(ALBERT CHUCKLING)
-WILL: Like, you just... (CHUCKLING)

25:37.911 --> 25:39.829
It's like, how did that get under there?

25:41.706 --> 25:44.251
All the way along,
from the moment I woke up...

25:45.252 --> 25:47.754
to being in this car,

25:48.505 --> 25:51.091
everything that we experienced

25:51.424 --> 25:54.427
was different than what I thought
it was gonna be...

25:55.720 --> 26:01.017
to the point that
I could see how my perception

26:01.101 --> 26:04.813
would have limited my experience
if I wasn't following you.

26:05.689 --> 26:08.233
And Namibia does that to me a lot.

26:08.733 --> 26:10.860
It's just different than I thought
it was gonna be.

26:10.944 --> 26:17.659
Whatever my frame of reference has been
for caves and water and sand,

26:17.867 --> 26:22.205
Namibia is destroying, at every turn,

26:22.539 --> 26:25.584
what I think something is going to be.

26:26.084 --> 26:28.878
Yeah, nature reveals itself
in the most incredible ways, right?

26:29.004 --> 26:33.049
Yeah, for sure. Now, that's the better way
to say what I wanted to say.

26:33.174 --> 26:34.843
-ALBERT: You can use it.
-"Nature reveal..." I can have it?

26:34.926 --> 26:36.052
-Thank you.
-ALBERT: Yeah, go for it.

26:36.136 --> 26:37.929
-I'm gonna put it on a t-shirt. Yeah.
-ALBERT: Do it, yeah.

26:38.305 --> 26:42.267
"Nature reveals itself
in such a beautiful way."

26:44.686 --> 26:46.104
<i>And we're not finished yet.</i>

26:47.397 --> 26:49.774
<i>Nature has more revealing to do.</i>

26:52.360 --> 26:54.154
<i>Nowhere more beautifully...</i>

26:56.197 --> 26:59.326
<i>than on the biggest salt flats</i>
<i>in the world.</i>

27:00.076 --> 27:04.956
(FLAMINGOS HONKING)

27:07.709 --> 27:12.589
(SERENE MUSIC PLAYING)

27:17.052 --> 27:20.055
WILL: <i>Those four and a half thousand miles</i>

27:20.221 --> 27:23.850
<i>can reveal speed</i>
<i>on an even more epic scale.</i>

27:25.143 --> 27:27.729
JHEISON:

27:38.239 --> 27:41.284
WILL: <i>Once a year,</i>
<i>the arrival of the rains...</i>

27:41.576 --> 27:45.163
-(THUNDER BOOMS)
<i>-...transform the vast salt flats...</i>

27:46.289 --> 27:50.877
<i>into a mirror so large</i>
<i>it seems to reflect everything.</i>

28:01.763 --> 28:02.889
(JHEISON SPEAKING IN SPANISH)

28:07.602 --> 28:08.645
JHEISON:

28:21.116 --> 28:23.702
WILL:<i> During the day, it's otherworldly.</i>

28:25.954 --> 28:26.955
(CAMERA BEEPS)

28:31.209 --> 28:33.044
WILL:<i> But it's when night falls</i>

28:33.628 --> 28:37.507
<i>that the true magic</i>
<i>of this cosmic mirror is revealed.</i>

29:00.238 --> 29:04.117
WILL: <i>A time-lapse shows us</i>
<i>the stars in motion.</i>

29:05.326 --> 29:07.829
<i>But lock the camera to the Milky Way,</i>

29:08.663 --> 29:11.458
<i>and you get to see</i>
<i>what's really going on up there.</i>

29:15.211 --> 29:18.089
<i>The movement is actually us.</i>

29:21.634 --> 29:27.474
<i>Our planet spinning on its axis</i>
<i>at 1,000 miles an hour.</i>

29:31.936 --> 29:35.899
<i>We can also tell that we're racing</i>
<i>through the solar system...</i>

29:36.983 --> 29:40.195
<i>at 67,000 miles an hour.</i>

29:41.362 --> 29:43.490
<i>And we're not even out of second gear yet.</i>

29:44.783 --> 29:49.287
Our entire galaxy is spinning
about its center.

29:51.164 --> 29:52.540
<i>By this time tomorrow,</i>

29:52.665 --> 29:56.878
<i>we will have hurtled</i>
<i>more than ten million miles through space.</i>

29:58.254 --> 30:00.882
Which is frighteningly fast.

30:03.676 --> 30:09.265
<i>But the Milky Way is so huge,</i>
<i>it's gonna take us 200 million years</i>

30:09.557 --> 30:11.100
<i>to go all the way around.</i>

30:12.393 --> 30:14.896
Which sounds painfully slow.

30:17.774 --> 30:19.651
<i>And the craziest thing of all...</i>

30:20.652 --> 30:25.615
<i>despite being hurled through space</i>
<i>at incomprehensible speeds...</i>

30:27.534 --> 30:29.577
<i>we can't feel any of it.</i>

30:29.744 --> 30:31.996
(SOFT WIND BLOWING)

30:33.373 --> 30:36.334
WILL: <i>So, is nothing happening here...</i>

30:39.003 --> 30:42.507
<i>or is the whole world invisibly moving?</i>

30:44.843 --> 30:47.095
<i>Albert's camera has the answer.</i>

30:48.513 --> 30:50.849
(SAND GRAINS RUSTLING)

30:56.980 --> 30:59.232
<i>ALBERT: You see, Will,</i>
<i>if we track the grains,</i>

30:59.691 --> 31:01.067
<i>you can watch how they bounce.</i>

31:05.071 --> 31:08.992
<i>That bouncing is happening</i>
<i>across this whole dune.</i>

31:21.713 --> 31:22.755
WILL: <i>That's crazy.</i>

31:24.674 --> 31:26.384
It's like it's moving like the ocean.

31:27.927 --> 31:32.098
ALBERT:<i> When we see all this,</i>
<i>these little waves marching towards us,</i>

31:32.724 --> 31:34.225
-it's happening.
-Yeah.

31:34.392 --> 31:37.687
It's just happening at a much slower pace,
beyond our perception.

31:38.229 --> 31:41.608
-And if we zoom out further...
-Wow!

31:46.237 --> 31:50.450
WILL: <i>The whole desert is in motion</i>
<i>right under our feet.</i>

31:52.035 --> 31:55.121
<i>And the fact</i>
<i>that it's constantly on the move</i>

31:55.455 --> 31:58.875
<i>is the reason it's stayed</i>
<i>a desert for so long.</i>

32:01.127 --> 32:03.129
<i>Nothing else can get a foothold here.</i>

32:04.297 --> 32:06.382
<i>No plants can anchor their roots.</i>

32:07.383 --> 32:10.053
<i>No animals can arrive to eat the plants.</i>

32:11.054 --> 32:13.514
<i>No town can build foundations.</i>

32:17.101 --> 32:20.605
<i>So, this desert is unchanging</i>

32:20.813 --> 32:25.151
<i>because it's always, always moving.</i>

32:26.027 --> 32:29.238
So, the appearance of permanence...

32:30.448 --> 32:35.787
is based on the power of its impermanence.

32:37.038 --> 32:40.458
You like that? That was just a little...
Just tossing a little poetry at you.

32:41.459 --> 32:44.128
-That was a big one, though.
-(LAUGHS)

32:50.510 --> 32:54.555
Our world is like
a series of clockwork cogs,

32:54.639 --> 32:56.557
all turning at different speeds.

32:58.351 --> 33:00.979
<i>Some too slow for us to see.</i>

33:03.439 --> 33:04.941
<i>Others, too fast.</i>

33:07.568 --> 33:10.530
<i>But all of them in constant motion.</i>

33:11.948 --> 33:13.574
<i>The animals around us...</i>

33:15.743 --> 33:17.537
<i>the land beneath us...</i>

33:19.747 --> 33:21.582
<i>and the universe above.</i>

33:23.751 --> 33:26.462
<i>Each is moving at its own pace...</i>

33:27.922 --> 33:29.424
<i>on its own cog.</i>

33:32.427 --> 33:36.472
<i>It's tempting to think</i>
<i>that what we see is all there is.</i>

33:38.891 --> 33:40.643
But every minute of every day,

33:40.727 --> 33:44.397
there are other realities
living alongside us.

33:44.731 --> 33:49.527
-Each one as perfect and precious as ours.
-ALBERT: Whoo!

33:50.236 --> 33:53.906
(BOTH LAUGH, CHEER)

33:59.162 --> 34:05.209
WILL:<i> Next time, the hidden world</i>
<i>is actually inside me.</i>

34:05.793 --> 34:10.339
Hello! My name is Will!

34:12.216 --> 34:14.969
<i>In a crazy, frozen wilderness,</i>

34:15.386 --> 34:21.392
<i>it's time to see if I've got</i>
<i>what it takes to be a true explorer.</i>

34:21.976 --> 34:24.020
-(SIGHS) You didn't kill me.
-(CHUCKLES)

34:24.395 --> 34:25.730
-(CHUCKLES)
-You didn't kill me.

34:26.064 --> 34:27.732
(BOTH LAUGHING)

